06204nam a22008175i 9780271091006DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212013pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710910067 a10.1515/97802710910062doi  a(DE-B1597)586195  a(OCoLC)1257323920  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aDG611.5b.S24 2013eb 7aHIS0370202bisacsh04a944/.5850322300aSabaudian Studies :bPolitical Culture, Dynasty, and Territory (1400-1700) /ced. by Matthew Vester. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEarly Modern Studies ;v1200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations and Maps -- tAbbreviations -- tDukes of Savoy, 1343-1730 -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 Sabaudian Studies -- tPolicies and Institutions -- t2 The Practice of Diplomacy at the Court of Amadeus VIII of Savoy (1391-1440) -- t3 Justice and Politics -- t4 From Piedmont to Tenochtitlan -- t5 Philibert-Albert Bailly, or The Origins of Valdostano Particularism -- tRepresenting the Dynasty -- tChapter 6 Recollecting Court Festivals -- tChapter 7 Charles Emanuel I's Foreign Policy -- tChapter 8 The Model of the Holy Savoyard Prince -- tChapter 9 The House of Savoy and the Theatre of the World -- tChapter 10 The Prolonged Minority of Charles Emanuel II -- tTerritorial Practices -- tChapter 11 Fiscality and Territory -- tChapter 12 Reshaping Local Public Space -- tChapter 13 Composite Politics in the Vallée d'Aoste -- tChapter 14 Sabaudian Spaces and Territories -- tPostscript -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis collection of interdisciplinary essays introduce the history and culture of the lands ruled by the sovereign house of Savoy during the late medieval and early modern periods, territories now part of France, Italy, and Switzerland. Because the Sabaudian realms were geographically, linguistically, and culturally diverse and did not evolve into a single modern nation-state, their early history has been overlooked by historians whose perspectives were often informed by a narrow, national framework.An international team of scholars offers new research that de-provincializes many of the existing rich scholarly assessments of the historical significance of these lands, which were important for rulers and subjects throughout early modern Europe. The volume explores the concept of "Sabaudian studies" and identifies historiographic developments and current trends in the field. Beginning with the geography and the history of the area, the essays examine Sabaudian political culture (diplomatic practice, judicial institutions, and political thought), dynastic representation (court festivals and celebrations, and the projection of dynastic prestige abroad, with attention to the sacred heritage of the house), and territorial domination (its fiscal, religious, feudal, and composite dimensions).Contributors include Eva Pibiri, Laurent Perrillat, Rebecca Boone, Alessandro Celi, Thalia Brero, Stéphane Gal and Preston Perluss, Michel Merle, Toby Osborne, Kristine Kolrud, Guido Alfani, Marco Battistoni, Matthew Vester, and Blythe Alice Raviola.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aPolitical culturezSavoy (France and Italy)xHistory. 7aHISTORY / Renaissance.2bisacsh1 aAlfani, Guido, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBattistoni, Marco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoone, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrero, Thalia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCeli, Alessandro, econtributor.